Nest algebras are an operator analogue of upper triangular matrices. They have been extensively
studied in the context of Hilbert spaces, but also in more general contexts.

Thanks! I think this still needs some massaging.
Thanks! I think this still needs some massaging.

1. There's nothing in this definition that needs `Nest` or even `Sublattice (Submodule R M)`.
2. Note that `T '' n \subset n` can now be phrased `n \in T.invtSubmodule`.
3. You can define, for a single submodule `p`, the subalgebra with carrier `{T | p \in T.invtSubmodule}`.
4. Then you can recover this subalgebra as the `\Inf` of these subalgebras over all submodules in a given set of submodules, it need not be a lattice or a nest.

Thanks.
```
def NestAlg (N : Set (Submodule R M)) : Subalgebra R (M →ₗ[R] M) where
  carrier := { T | ∀ (n : N), ↑n ∈ Module.End.invtSubmodule (T : Module.End R M)}
```
also seems to work - but perhaps there is some advantage to defining the subalgebra generated by a single submodule first?
You only need `LinearIndependent` for this construction, not `Basis`. With `Basis` you can construct a `Flag` (at least for fintypes, but I think in general too?)
Mathlib already has `Basis.toFlag` for the finite dim case. I'll see if it works in the general case too.
This is *far* too heavy an import. Just create a new file if there isn't a better place.
